\subsection{Multi-Concept Interference Analysis}
\label{app:interference}

Interference under simultaneous erasure (Table~\ref{table:dual_all}) depends on how much the two concepts share the \emph{person} region:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=1.5em,itemsep=2pt]
    \item \textbf{Low interference}: Nudity~$+$~Shocking ($-9.4$\%p on nudity). These concepts occupy largely disjoint semantic regions; families further decouple them.
    \item \textbf{Moderate}: Nudity~$+$~Violence ($-5.2$\%p), Nudity~$+$~Harassment ($-12.2$\%p). Shared person-level semantics cause mild overlap, but family masks keep masks narrow.
    \item \textbf{High}: Nudity~$+$~Hate ($-26.0$\%p). Strong overlap in human-subject regions; future work should adapt per-concept $\tau$ or route guidance through a shared arbiter.
\end{itemize}
A single pooled vector per concept collapses all sub-categories into one direction, which inflates interference by design; per-family anchors localize the fight to the sub-category actually present.

\subsection{CAS Threshold Sensitivity}
\label{app:cas_threshold}

Varying $\tau$ from 0.3 to 0.7 on Ring-A-Bell with hybrid guidance shows:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=1.5em,itemsep=2pt]
    \item $\tau{=}0.3$: aggressive --- high nudity SR, elevated COCO false positives ($>8\%$).
    \item $\tau{=}0.5$--$0.6$: optimal SR-vs-FP trade-off for nudity.
    \item $\tau{=}0.7$: conservative --- $<2\%$ false positives but missed detections.
    \item Violence and shocking prefer $\tau{=}0.4$: their family-level alignment signal is lower-magnitude on average but stays consistent across families.
\end{itemize}

\section{Evaluator Validation Details}
\label{app:evaluator}

The main paper reports the Safety-Recovery rate SR under a four-class VLM rubric rather than a binary safety detector. This choice is not aesthetic: binary detectors such as NudeNet~\citep{notai_nudenet_2019} and CLIP-based classifiers such as Q16~\citep{schramowski2022can} systematically conflate two distinct failure modes---over-sensitivity on benign content and collapse-as-safety on destroyed generations---that a \emph{semantic-preserving} erasure method (§\ref{sec:method}) must be able to tell apart. This appendix establishes three properties of our evaluator, in order. (C.1--C.3)~Qwen3-VL-8B matches or exceeds published proprietary VLM judges on the standard MJ-Bench safety protocol, so it is a competitive choice in absolute terms. (C.4)~No binary or CLIP-embedding detector admits a drop-in replacement, because both families treat semantic collapse as \emph{safer} than the original unsafe prompt---a pathology that is directly incompatible with the main-paper thesis. (C.5)~Qwen3-VL-8B's per-image label tracks a human-majority annotation on a stratified I2P audit, so the SR numbers reported throughout are faithful to human-perceived safety rather than to an isolated model idiosyncrasy.

\subsection{MJ-Bench Safety Evaluation Protocol}
\label{app:mjbench_protocol}

We validate Qwen3-VL-8B as a safety judge on MJ-Bench~\citep{chen2024mj} (672 safety pairs). Unlike the full MJ-Bench five-criteria benchmark (alignment, aesthetics, artifacts, safety, bias \& fairness), we evaluate only the \textbf{safety} criterion: safety judgment is the sole role of the evaluator throughout our paper. For each pair, both images are presented simultaneously to Qwen3-VL-8B-Instruct with a multi-image comparison prompt that assigns a safety score on a $1$--$10$ scale to each image and selects the safer one (ties allowed). Accuracy is reported with ties counted as incorrect (``w/ tie''), with ties excluded from the denominator (``w/o tie''), and as their average (``Avg'') for an overall summary.

