\subsection{Why a Four-Class VLM Rubric Is Necessary}
\label{app:evaluator_extended}

The main paper frames concept erasure as \emph{semantic-preserving}: an unsafe prompt must map to one of three qualitatively distinct outcomes---(i)~\textsc{Full}, the unsafe concept is clearly present; (ii)~\textsc{Safe}/\textsc{Partial}, the unsafe concept is suppressed but the benign portion of the prompt remains visible; (iii)~\textsc{NotPeople}/\textsc{NotRelevant}, the generation has collapsed to noise, artifacts, or an unrelated scene. Binary safety detectors and CLIP-based classifiers collapse (ii) and (iii) into a single ``safe'' decision, which directly rewards safety-by-destruction and invalidates the evaluation for any method that targets (ii) without (iii). We make this argument in three steps: (\S\ref{app:evaluator_limits})~detector-level failure modes on the over-sensitivity axis, (\S\ref{app:evaluator_collapse})~protocol-level failure modes on the semantic-collapse axis, and (\S\ref{app:evaluator_vlm})~how the four-class VLM rubric resolves both.

\subsubsection{Limitations of Existing Evaluation Metrics}
\label{app:evaluator_limits}

Safety-oriented diffusion studies targeting nudity or sexually explicit content are commonly evaluated with automated nudity detectors and classifier-based safety metrics for their scalability. NudeNet~\citep{notai_nudenet_2019} is widely adopted as a default tool that produces a coarse binary nudity decision. Several works report CLIP-based safety classifiers (\eg, Q16~\citep{schramowski2022can}) as a complementary signal, which estimate inappropriateness through image-text similarity against curated descriptors rather than by direct semantic verification.

Both families exhibit systematic limitations for safety \emph{with} semantic preservation. \emph{First}, coarse nudity detectors conflate benign exposure (\eg, swimwear, athletic attire, portraits with visible shoulders) with genuinely harmful content, yielding a steady stream of false positives that incentivize over-suppression (Figure~\ref{fig:case_oversensitivity}); a method that uniformly darkens or blurs human skin will score better than a method that preserves a fully-clothed subject, which is the opposite of what a deployment would want. \emph{Second}, embedding-based safety classifiers are not designed to assess whether an image remains semantically coherent; they can assign a low-risk score even when the generation has degenerated into artifacts, blur, or off-distribution noise, because the discriminative signal they rely on (``does the CLIP embedding resemble the nudity descriptors?'') saturates on degenerate inputs. Consequently, detector-only evaluation risks \emph{misidentifying semantic collapse as safety}, which is fundamentally misaligned with human judgment.

