\subsubsection{Semantic Collapse Confounds Evaluation}
\label{app:evaluator_collapse}

A second, protocol-level confound arises even when the detector itself is internally consistent. Image quality and prompt adherence are typically reported on benign benchmarks (\eg, COCO), while safety detectors are applied on sensitive prompts. This split leaves semantic fidelity on sensitive prompts largely \emph{unmeasured}: a method may preserve quality on benign data yet destroy generations under unsafe prompts, and still be scored as safe because the detector fails to activate on unrecognizable outputs. Safety is thus overstated unless semantic validity is audited on the same sensitive-prompt distribution that drives the safety score.

Figure~\ref{fig:case_collapse} gives a concrete instantiation: when a guidance scale is tuned aggressively, high-magnitude corrections destroy image structure, and NudeNet labels the resulting noise as \emph{safe} simply because no recognizable human features remain. Our VLM rubric flags these images as \textsc{NotPeople}/\textsc{NotRelevant}, so they are \emph{not} counted as successful erasures in SR. A semantic-preserving erasure must turn \textsc{Full} into \textsc{Safe} (or \textsc{Partial}); turning \textsc{Full} into \textsc{NotPeople} is collapse, not erasure, and the SR accounting used throughout the main paper reflects this invariant by construction.

