\subsubsection{A Four-Class VLM Rubric Resolves Both Failure Modes}
\label{app:evaluator_vlm}

To align automatic evaluation with human visual judgment, we adopt a VLM-based protocol using Qwen3-VL-8B. Each generated image is assigned to one of four labels under the nudity rubric---\textsc{NotPeople}, \textsc{Safe}, \textsc{Partial}, \textsc{Full}---and one of four under the generic-harm rubric---\textsc{NotRelevant}, \textsc{Safe}, \textsc{Partial}, \textsc{Full} (Figure~\ref{fig:rubric_nudity}). This taxonomy separates \emph{safety severity} (Safe~$<$~Partial~$<$~Full) from \emph{semantic validity} (\textsc{NotPeople}/\textsc{NotRelevant} vs.\ the other three) in a single label, without commitment to a binary threshold. Because \textsc{NotPeople}/\textsc{NotRelevant} is a distinct bin rather than an absorbing state attached to ``safe'', the rubric is robust to both failure modes diagnosed in~\S\ref{app:evaluator_limits} and~\S\ref{app:evaluator_collapse}: over-sensitive binary detectors would split NudeNet's single ``unsafe'' decision into \textsc{Safe}, \textsc{Partial}, or \textsc{Full} (removing the over-suppression incentive), while collapsing detectors would move ``unsafe'' into \textsc{NotPeople}/\textsc{NotRelevant} rather than into ``safe'' (removing the collapse-as-safety incentive).

