This is \emph{not} a claim that VLM judges are infallible: it is a claim that the rubric shape---four classes, with \textsc{NotPeople}/\textsc{NotRelevant} as a separate bin---rules out the pathologies that make NudeNet/Q16 unsuitable for evaluating semantic-preserving erasure. The residual concern---that the VLM's per-image label may still diverge from human perception on individual images---is addressed by the human-agreement audit in~\S\ref{app:human_study}.

\subsection{Human Agreement Study}
\label{app:human_study}

\paragraph{Purpose.}
Directly validate that Qwen3-VL-8B's four-class label matches the label a pool of human annotators converges on, so that the main-paper SR numbers are a meaningful proxy for human-perceived safety.

\paragraph{Protocol.}
\emph{Annotators.} Approximately 20 adult annotators recruited under content-warning consent, English-literate, task-compensated; opt-out is allowed at any time. \emph{Stimuli.} For each of the eight I2P concepts we sample 100 generated images from the I2P test set, balanced across methods (baseline, SAFREE, \ours{}-anchor, \ours{}-hybrid), yielding $8 \times 100 = 800$ images total. \emph{Task.} Each image is presented with a one-paragraph compressed form of the rubric in Figure~\ref{fig:rubric_nudity}, and each annotator classifies the image as one of \{\textsc{Full}, \textsc{Partial}, \textsc{Safe}, \textsc{NotRelevant} (or \textsc{NotPeople} for nudity)\} under forced choice. \emph{Ground truth.} Per-image ground truth is the \emph{majority vote} across the $\sim\!20$ annotators. \emph{VLM agreement.} For every image we compare Qwen3-VL-8B's label against the human majority and report two metrics: \textbf{exact-match agreement} (identical labels) and \textbf{within-1 accuracy} (the VLM label is at most one rubric step away from the majority, \eg \textsc{Partial} vs.\ \textsc{Safe} counts as within-1 but \textsc{Full} vs.\ \textsc{Safe} does not).

