\section{Cross-Backbone Validation (Full Results)}
\label{app:cross_backbone_full}

The main body (\S\ref{subsec:cross_backbone}) summarizes the cross-backbone validation; this appendix reports the full per-concept numbers and the architectural take-away. Only the Where probe is re-implemented per backbone---cross-attention for SD~v1.4 UNet, a joint-attention sub-matrix for SD~3 MMDiT, and a DiT-compatible spatial probe for FLUX.1-dev---while the CAS gate (Eq.~\ref{eq:cas}) and both How updates (Eqs.~\ref{eq:anchor_inpaint}--\ref{eq:hybrid}) are reused verbatim. Table~\ref{table:cross_backbone} reports MJA SR per concept on all three backbones.

\input{table/cross_backbone}

\paragraph{What transfers.}
On FLUX.1-dev the two-mode trade-off observed on SD~v1.4 replicates: hybrid dominates on concepts with a visually crisp paired anchor (sexual, disturbing), while anchor inpainting dominates on concepts with ambiguous anchors (violent, illegal). This is evidence that the trade-off is a property of the \emph{concept pack and CFG geometry}, not of the $\epsilon$-prediction UNet. On SD~3 (MMDiT) we report only the anchor row in this revision: the CAS threshold $\tau{=}0.6$ was calibrated for $\epsilon$-prediction and lies above SD~3's velocity-parameterization CAS range ($0.03$--$0.51$), so hybrid guidance is effectively never triggered under that threshold. A per-backbone $\tau$ retune is in progress (we expect $\tau \in [0.2, 0.4]$ for SD~3) and the corresponding cells will be filled once the sweep stabilizes; we deliberately do \emph{not} report contaminated SD~3 hybrid numbers.

\paragraph{What this validates.}
The take-away is architectural rather than purely numerical. CAS is a cosine of \emph{direction differences} and both How modes are \emph{linear} in the prediction, so the When and How components are identical up to a per-backbone scale; only Where requires per-backbone re-implementation. The fact that concept-level trends---image-dominant concepts benefit from the image probe across all three backbones; hybrid-vs-anchor winners align between SD~v1.4 and FLUX---transfer across $\epsilon$-prediction, velocity, and flow-matching parameterizations is what converts \ours{} from an SD~v1.4-specific recipe into a \emph{framework} usable on any backbone for which a spatial probe can be extracted from the denoiser.

\section{Limitations and Failure Cases}
\label{app:limitations}

We group the limitations of \ours{} along four axes that correspond to the three-stage When/Where/How decomposition of the main paper, plus one evaluator-side caveat.

\paragraph{When: adversarial robustness of the CAS gate.}
On the strongest adversarial benchmark, MMA-Diffusion~\citep{yang2024mma}, \ours{} still misses approximately $20\%$ of sophisticated jailbreaks whose CAS stays below $\tau$ for the entire denoising trajectory. These prompts do not align strongly with any concept-level descriptor pack in cosine space, so the gate never fires and the pipeline is effectively bypassed. Lowering $\tau$ uniformly is not a fix: benign-prompt false-positive rates on COCO rise above $8\%$ at $\tau{=}0.3$ (\S\ref{app:cas_threshold}). Learned or prompt-aware $\tau$ selection on a small validation split is a promising direction but left for future work.

\paragraph{Where: concept overlap in multi-concept erasure.}
When two concepts share the person region (\eg, nudity$+$hate), per-family masks overlap, and the pixel-wise winner-take-all resolves the conflict by selecting whichever (concept, family) has the stronger per-pixel score. The \emph{losing} (concept, family), however, then contributes no guidance on that pixel. Family packs mitigate but do not eliminate destructive interference in this regime (Table~\ref{table:dual_all}); the largest drop we observe is $-26.0$~pp on nudity for the nudity$+$hate pair. A more principled arbiter---\eg, a soft cross-concept mixture rather than a hard partition---is a natural next step.

\paragraph{How: per-backbone re-tuning of magnitudes.}
CAS and both How updates are parameterization-invariant in form but not in magnitude: $\tau$ and the guidance scale (particularly $s_\text{h}$ on hybrid) require per-backbone re-calibration because the CFG direction's magnitude depends on the denoiser's output parameterization (\S\ref{app:cross_backbone_full}). Hyperparameter transfer between backbones is a practical limitation and likely not fully resolvable without a principled normalization of the CFG direction.

\paragraph{Evaluator.}
The main-paper SR numbers rely on Qwen3-VL-8B as the sole safety judge (\S\ref{app:evaluator}). MJ-Bench (\S\ref{app:mjbench_table1}) and the in-progress human-agreement study (\S\ref{app:human_study}) provide strong evidence of judge reliability, but any single-evaluator protocol carries residual risk; we will release per-image labels at camera-ready so that downstream studies can re-score under alternative judges.

\section{Broader Impact}
\label{app:broader_impact}

\ours{} is designed to mitigate safety concerns in generative models and contributes to responsible deployment of T2I diffusion systems. The same spatial localization techniques could, in principle, be repurposed to \emph{amplify} harmful content if applied maliciously---running the pipeline with swapped target/anchor directions would push the generation \emph{toward} the concept rather than away from it. We therefore recommend deploying \ours{} as one component of a comprehensive safety pipeline that also includes upstream prompt filtering and downstream content review. We release the concept packs used in our evaluation as human-readable prompt-and-image directories so that practitioners and auditors can inspect, extend, or contest the safety policy directly, rather than relying on an opaque classifier.
